---

### In a nutshell...

..."tondo" means a circular work of art. It is a Renaissance term, derived from the Italian word rotondo, and are usually for round paintings that are over 60cm in diameter.
Because the painting is a circle shape and not your standard vertical/horizontal rectangle, everything in the work needs to follow the round shape.

## An example

![Sandro Botticelli, *Madonna della Melagrana* (1487)](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/04/Madonna_della_Melagrana_%28Botticelli%29.png/800px-Madonna_della_Melagrana_%28Botticelli%29.png)

Look at this painting by Botticelli[^1] as an example. See how all of the figures are leaning in towards Madonna (who is in the centre). Their shapes conform to the circular format

![Botticelli Circle](data:image/png;base64,)

See how the figures in this painting follow the shape/arch of the painting? They are leaning forward to avoid being cropped out by the frame. This means that the shape of the painting helps to define the composition of what's inside it!

Tondo was a very popular composition device used by many Italian artists, including Botticelli. Look out for it when looking through Italian models of practice!

---

[^1]: Sandro Botticelli, *Madonna della Melagrana* (1487)
